{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568878"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:23:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:23:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21498"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21498"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.06,0.03,0.07,0.83]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14367"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102546"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14367"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21498"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85020"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"380"},{"type":"tags","id":"3501"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"35856"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102546"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman at 30 weeks gestation presents with a three-week history of tingling and numbness in her right thumb, index, and middle fingers. The symptoms are worse at night and when driving. She reports shaking her hand provides temporary relief. On examination, there is no visible muscle wasting or weakness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following physical examination manoeuvres is most specific for confirming carpal tunnel syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Compression of the ulnar nerve at the elbow","Passive extension of the fingers against resistance","Resisted pronation of the forearm","Abduction of the thumb against resistance","Percussion over the median nerve at the wrist"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercussion over the median nerve at the wrist\u003C/strong\u003E (Tinel\u0027s sign) is a specific test for carpal tunnel syndrome. This involves tapping over the median nerve as it passes through the carpal tunnel, which reproduces the patient\u0027s symptoms of tingling or electric shock-like sensations in the median nerve distribution if carpal tunnel syndrome is present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnother useful test is Phalen\u0027s sign, which involves having the patient hold their wrists in complete flexion for approximately 60 seconds. This position increases pressure on the median nerve and reproduces symptoms in patients with carpal tunnel syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive extension of the fingers against resistance\u003C/strong\u003E - This tests finger extensor strength and is not specific for carpal tunnel syndrome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResisted pronation of the forearm\u003C/strong\u003E - This tests the strength of the pronator teres muscle, which is not typically affected in carpal tunnel syndrome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompression of the ulnar nerve at the elbow\u003C/strong\u003E - This tests for ulnar nerve compression (cubital tunnel syndrome), not median nerve compression\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbduction of the thumb against resistance\u003C/strong\u003E - While this tests the abductor pollicis brevis which can be affected in advanced carpal tunnel syndrome, it is testing for weakness rather than reproducing the sensory symptoms\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECarpal tunnel syndrome is common during pregnancy due to increased fluid retention causing compression of the median nerve at the wrist. It typically presents with sensory symptoms in the distribution of the median nerve (thumb, index, middle, and radial half of the ring finger).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carpal tunnel syndrome is common in pregnancy due to fluid retention causing median nerve compression at the wrist.","Tinel\u0027s sign involves percussion over the carpal tunnel to reproduce symptoms of median nerve compression.","Phalen\u0027s sign involves sustained wrist flexion for 60 seconds to reproduce symptoms of median nerve compression."],"references":["Nelson-Piercy C. Handbook of obstetric medicine. 6th ed. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85020"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21498"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85020"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-13T03:11:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-13T03:12:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14367"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102546"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"